WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.790 --> 00:00:06.490
&gt;&gt; From the Library of
Congress in Washington D.C.

00:00:06.490 --> 00:00:11.510
&gt;&gt; Carla Hayden: I'm Carla
Hayden, Librarian of Congress.

00:00:11.510 --> 00:00:17.150
[ Applause ]

00:00:17.150 --> 00:00:23.550
And this has been my first national
book festival as the Librarian

00:00:23.550 --> 00:00:27.680
of Congress and what
a day it has been.

00:00:27.680 --> 00:00:33.600 position:56%
I have learned so much about the
outstanding writers who participated

00:00:33.600 --> 00:00:36.560
in this event and I
will never forget all

00:00:36.560 --> 00:00:41.990
of the book lovers I have seen
from all ages, all backgrounds,

00:00:41.990 --> 00:00:47.820
and I just came back from the
poetry slam and I have to tell you

00:00:47.820 --> 00:00:50.890
if you want to see raw
talent and emotion,

00:00:50.890 --> 00:00:52.820
next year you have to be there.

00:00:52.820 --> 00:00:54.640
It was wonderful.

00:00:54.640 --> 00:01:01.940
And I'm especially pleased to
be able to present to you one

00:01:01.940 --> 00:01:09.950
of the greatest authors that I've
met because he is the Library

00:01:09.950 --> 00:01:12.530
of Congress' National Ambassador

00:01:12.530 --> 00:01:18.510
for Young People's
Literature, Gene Luen Yang.

00:01:18.510 --> 00:01:25.210
[ Applause ]

00:01:25.210 --> 00:01:29.780
And I'm going to congratulate
him once again

00:01:29.780 --> 00:01:34.510
for being named a MacArthur Genius.

00:01:34.510 --> 00:01:40.310
[ Applause ]

00:01:40.310 --> 00:01:43.810
Gene is the fifth National
Ambassador

00:01:43.810 --> 00:01:45.470
for Young People's Literature

00:01:45.470 --> 00:01:49.040
and the first graphic artist
to hold this position.

00:01:49.040 --> 00:01:51.300
And before we get to his program,

00:01:51.300 --> 00:01:53.900
I just want to make a
special announcement.

00:01:53.900 --> 00:01:57.690
Mark your calendars
for September 2, 2017.

00:01:57.690 --> 00:02:01.400
That will be the date of
the next book festival,

00:02:01.400 --> 00:02:04.290
right here at the Washington
Convention Center.

00:02:04.290 --> 00:02:07.010
So, I hope you can attend.

00:02:07.010 --> 00:02:12.500
Back to Gene and enjoy and
thank you all for being here.

00:02:12.500 --> 00:02:14.500
[ Applause ]

00:02:18.440 --> 00:02:21.360
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna: All right.

00:02:21.360 --> 00:02:24.580
Hi. How do you follow that?

00:02:24.580 --> 00:02:30.470
How do you follow a historic
new leader of this institution

00:02:30.470 --> 00:02:33.790
between her and a brand new genius?

00:02:33.790 --> 00:02:36.790
It's just, you know,
we'll do what we can.

00:02:36.790 --> 00:02:40.420
But, my name is Michael
Cavna, a columnist cartoonist

00:02:40.420 --> 00:02:41.720
with the Washington Post.

00:02:41.720 --> 00:02:45.320 position:56%
I do the Comic Riffs blog and I also
did the syndicated strip Warp you

00:02:45.320 --> 00:02:48.560
can find at gocomics.com.

00:02:48.560 --> 00:02:53.080
I've spent a lifetime in comics
and a lifetime as an art senator

00:02:53.080 --> 00:02:57.300
and believe that graphic novels
are one of the most important

00:02:57.300 --> 00:02:59.030
and crucial forms of communication

00:02:59.030 --> 00:03:01.620
for young readers,
for reluctant readers.

00:03:01.620 --> 00:03:04.270
I come from a tribe of educators.

00:03:04.270 --> 00:03:06.120
We have an educator here.

00:03:06.120 --> 00:03:07.990
Educators are my people.

00:03:07.990 --> 00:03:10.730
So, three years ago,
when my daughter was

00:03:10.730 --> 00:03:14.670
in a nearby school
and she had read Maus.

00:03:14.670 --> 00:03:17.050
And she comes home, she's
sad, she's almost crying.

00:03:17.050 --> 00:03:18.350
I said what's wrong.

00:03:18.350 --> 00:03:21.390
She said my teacher said
graphic novels aren't books.

00:03:21.390 --> 00:03:26.290
Can imagine my response to that, so
I went and marched to the principal

00:03:26.290 --> 00:03:30.060
and the principal said, oh, yeah,
graphic novels aren't books.

00:03:30.060 --> 00:03:32.940
So, I spent the next year
proving, in the Post,

00:03:32.940 --> 00:03:35.400
that graphic novels are books.

00:03:35.400 --> 00:03:38.270
And one of the first people I went
to, I thought who is an educator,

00:03:38.270 --> 00:03:43.370 position:56%
who understands librarians, and who
is a great graphic novelist himself?

00:03:43.370 --> 00:03:48.000
And who just happened to be coming
through town but Mr. Gene Luen Yang

00:03:48.000 --> 00:03:53.210 position:56%
and we walked around the Post and we
shot a little video and at the end

00:03:53.210 --> 00:03:57.600
of the year we had an
award-winning serious that proved--

00:03:57.600 --> 00:04:01.180
the judges said once and for
all graphic novels are books.

00:04:01.180 --> 00:04:05.030
So, that educator isn't very far
north of here, so do you mind just

00:04:05.030 --> 00:04:10.660
as a favor to me one time saying,
for me, graphic novels are books.

00:04:10.660 --> 00:04:12.610
On three. One, two, three.

00:04:12.610 --> 00:04:15.470
Graphic novels are books.

00:04:15.470 --> 00:04:16.770
Thank you.

00:04:16.770 --> 00:04:18.600
I needed that.

00:04:18.600 --> 00:04:19.900
I needed that.

00:04:19.900 --> 00:04:23.690
And we have an institution
here wise enough to know that.

00:04:23.690 --> 00:04:30.910
It is my true pleasure to have
Gene Luen Yang as our headliner,

00:04:30.910 --> 00:04:32.210
finishing off this night.

00:04:32.210 --> 00:04:36.620 position:56%
It was January when we were not far
from here in the Library of Congress

00:04:36.620 --> 00:04:40.020
and Gene was being inaugurated
as the National Ambassador

00:04:40.020 --> 00:04:44.480
for Young People's Literature and
they couldn't have chosen better.

00:04:44.480 --> 00:04:47.290
He began drawing comic
books in the fifth grade.

00:04:47.290 --> 00:04:51.430 position:56%
In '97, he received a Xeric Grant
for his first comic, Gordon Yamamoto

00:04:51.430 --> 00:04:52.840
and the King of the Geeks.

00:04:52.840 --> 00:04:54.980
Here is a man who proudly
calls himself a geek.

00:04:54.980 --> 00:04:58.260
He has written things
like Duncan's Kingdom,

00:04:58.260 --> 00:05:02.300
the Rosemary Comic
Book, Animal Crackers.

00:05:02.300 --> 00:05:05.360
It was a decade ago,
American Born Chinese,

00:05:05.360 --> 00:05:07.040
a brilliant cross-culture book.

00:05:07.040 --> 00:05:09.560
Yes. Brilliant.

00:05:09.560 --> 00:05:11.950
So many beautiful metaphors
all threading through.

00:05:11.950 --> 00:05:18.000
Became the first graphic novel to
be a National Book Award finalist.

00:05:18.000 --> 00:05:21.290
He followed that up with such
projects as Boxers and Saints,

00:05:21.290 --> 00:05:24.310
which also was a National
Book Award finalist.

00:05:24.310 --> 00:05:30.160
So, I think you're due pretty soon
for a third one in about a year.

00:05:30.160 --> 00:05:33.490
He is just-- he did a brilliant
book about the Shadow Hero.

00:05:33.490 --> 00:05:35.120
You should definitely
check that out.

00:05:35.120 --> 00:05:37.930
He won an Eisner for
the Eternal Smile

00:05:37.930 --> 00:05:41.630
and now he's doing this
wonderful-- he's, again, sneaking--

00:05:41.630 --> 00:05:44.670
now he's sneaking education
into the graphic novels

00:05:44.670 --> 00:05:47.090
with this series Secret Coders.

00:05:47.090 --> 00:05:50.520
It's part comic, but you read
it and realize he's getting kids

00:05:50.520 --> 00:05:55.240
to do problems, to solve, to think,
and that's part of his genius.

00:05:55.240 --> 00:05:58.890
He taught high school for
nearly two decades in Oakland.

00:05:58.890 --> 00:06:03.090
He's working on a long project,
Dragon Hoops about that teams--

00:06:03.090 --> 00:06:05.440
that basketball team,
a diverse team.

00:06:05.440 --> 00:06:07.670
He just does it all.

00:06:07.670 --> 00:06:12.160
He even-- on top of Avatar: The
Last Airbender, on the side,

00:06:12.160 --> 00:06:14.360
writing Superman-- just to
kind of through that in.

00:06:14.360 --> 00:06:17.010
A think that's a lifelong
dream for many people,

00:06:17.010 --> 00:06:18.530
he's just throwing that in there.

00:06:18.530 --> 00:06:20.900
So, he's doing it all.

00:06:20.900 --> 00:06:23.670
He just-- he's-- I've
had the pleasure

00:06:23.670 --> 00:06:25.820
of moderating him numerous times.

00:06:25.820 --> 00:06:29.810
He's just a fantastic
talent, a fantastic voice,

00:06:29.810 --> 00:06:34.030
and a fantastic ambassador, I
believe globally, for comics.

00:06:34.030 --> 00:06:36.570
Please welcome Gene Luen Yang.

00:06:36.570 --> 00:06:38.510
&gt;&gt; Gene Luen Yang: Thank you.

00:06:38.510 --> 00:06:44.040
[ Applause ]

00:06:44.040 --> 00:06:52.120
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna: So--
and-- all right.

00:06:52.120 --> 00:06:54.160
Well, thank you for coming here.

00:06:54.160 --> 00:06:55.460
&gt;&gt; Gene Luen Yang: Yeah,
thank you for having me.

00:06:55.460 --> 00:07:01.140
Thank you all for being here,
especially at the very end.

00:07:01.140 --> 00:07:02.440
Thank you so much.

00:07:02.440 --> 00:07:03.740
And thank you to Michael.

00:07:03.740 --> 00:07:07.500 position:56%
I don't know if you all know this,
but Michael is kind of like a ninja.

00:07:07.500 --> 00:07:11.810
You know? He's at the post, he
