00:08:53.260 --> 00:08:54.560
&gt;&gt; Gene Luen Yang: Well,
first, that's my second goal.

00:08:54.560 --> 00:08:56.140
I want my wife to call
me Mr. Universe.

00:08:56.140 --> 00:08:57.850
That would be awesome.

00:08:57.850 --> 00:08:59.500
But it's been great.

00:08:59.500 --> 00:09:03.130
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna: For 625,000
you might be able to-- yeah.

00:09:03.130 --> 00:09:04.610
&gt;&gt; Gene Luen Yang: It's been great.

00:09:04.610 --> 00:09:06.260
It's been a little bit hectic.

00:09:06.260 --> 00:09:09.390
I think this is one of the most
hectic years I have ever lived,

00:09:09.390 --> 00:09:10.890
but it's also been awesome.

00:09:10.890 --> 00:09:14.780
I love going to schools
and talking to kids about--

00:09:14.780 --> 00:09:17.660
not just comics, but
books and reading.

00:09:17.660 --> 00:09:21.420
And about how sometimes we put up
these artificial walls, right--

00:09:21.420 --> 00:09:23.430
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna: I was going to
say, can you talk about you theme?

00:09:23.430 --> 00:09:25.000
Your message?

00:09:25.000 --> 00:09:28.120
&gt;&gt; Gene Luen Yang: So, every
ambassador picks a platform,

00:09:28.120 --> 00:09:30.680
the platform I chose is
reading without walls and by

00:09:30.680 --> 00:09:34.820
that I just mean I want kids to
explore the world through books

00:09:34.820 --> 00:09:37.110
and I want them to do it
in three specific ways.

00:09:37.110 --> 00:09:40.410
Number one is I want them to choose
books about people who don't look

00:09:40.410 --> 00:09:41.980
like them or live like them.

00:09:41.980 --> 00:09:44.960
Two is I want them to
choose books about topics

00:09:44.960 --> 00:09:46.860
that they might find intimidating.

00:09:46.860 --> 00:09:49.830
And, three, I want them
to choose books in formats

00:09:49.830 --> 00:09:51.840
that they might not
normally read for fun.

00:09:51.840 --> 00:09:54.850
So, if you're a kid that
normally only reads chapter books,

00:09:54.850 --> 00:09:58.480
I want you to try a graphic
novel or a book in verse.

00:09:58.480 --> 00:10:00.030 position:56%
And if you only read graphic novels,

00:10:00.030 --> 00:10:03.140
I want you to try a chapter
book, any sort of other thing.

00:10:03.140 --> 00:10:04.440
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna: Yeah.

00:10:04.440 --> 00:10:08.020
So, did you practice
what you preach as a kid?

00:10:08.020 --> 00:10:10.080
You were doing comics,
but, you know, you,

00:10:10.080 --> 00:10:12.080
you know, you're brilliant.

00:10:12.080 --> 00:10:14.250
You know, your knowledge in
computer programming is brilliant,

00:10:14.250 --> 00:10:15.550
but were you reading everything?

00:10:15.550 --> 00:10:17.180
Were you sort of open?

00:10:17.180 --> 00:10:19.090
Did comics help you
break down other walls?

00:10:19.090 --> 00:10:20.540
&gt;&gt; Gene Luen Yang: Well, one of
the reasons I wanted to do reading

00:10:20.540 --> 00:10:22.080
without walls is because
it's something

00:10:22.080 --> 00:10:25.180
that I would tell myself
to do when I was a kid.

00:10:25.180 --> 00:10:27.430
I do remember-- I went
to the library a lot,

00:10:27.430 --> 00:10:29.450
mostly because my mom took us.

00:10:29.450 --> 00:10:31.120
Took me and my brother.

00:10:31.120 --> 00:10:33.940
It was sort of a free
babysitter, I think.

00:10:33.940 --> 00:10:35.290
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna: Was
this in the Bay Area?

00:10:35.290 --> 00:10:36.590
&gt;&gt; Gene Luen Yang: It
was in the Bay Area.

00:10:36.590 --> 00:10:37.890
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna: I-- literally,

00:10:37.890 --> 00:10:39.190
my mom at the same time
taking us to the library.

00:10:39.190 --> 00:10:41.820
We might have been at the same
library in the same comic aisle.

00:10:41.820 --> 00:10:43.150
OK. Yeah.

00:10:43.150 --> 00:10:44.450
&gt;&gt; Gene Luen Yang: Well,
that's the thing is that with--

00:10:44.450 --> 00:10:47.470
I remember at my local
library we didn't really have

00:10:47.470 --> 00:10:49.220
that great of a YA section.

00:10:49.220 --> 00:10:52.900
It kind of went from J to adult
and there was nothing in-between.

00:10:52.900 --> 00:10:56.800
I remember getting to like fourth,
fifth, sixth grade and starting

00:10:56.800 --> 00:10:58.740
to feel a little bit lost
at the library and that's

00:10:58.740 --> 00:11:00.040
when I discovered comics.

00:11:00.040 --> 00:11:01.340
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna: Yeah.

00:11:01.340 --> 00:11:02.640
And they filled something for you.

00:11:02.640 --> 00:11:03.940
Filled that gap.

00:11:03.940 --> 00:11:05.240
Yeah. What was your
first comic that you--

00:11:05.240 --> 00:11:08.190 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Gene Luen Yang: The very first
comic I got was a DC Comics Presents

00:11:08.190 --> 00:11:11.670
