00:43:09.450 --> 00:43:14.280
web culture has changed things,
but discovering the appeal

00:43:14.280 --> 00:43:19.760
of certain books to girls,
YA classrooms, we-- that--

00:43:19.760 --> 00:43:22.370
I believe that's another area where
we're seeing a revolution, right?

00:43:22.370 --> 00:43:23.670
&gt;&gt; Gene Luen Yang: We are.

00:43:23.670 --> 00:43:24.970
We are.

00:43:24.970 --> 00:43:27.260
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna: It feels-- I have
a daughter and it feels massive.

00:43:27.260 --> 00:43:28.560
Can you talk about that?

00:43:28.560 --> 00:43:29.860
&gt;&gt; Gene Luen Yang:
It's hugely massive.

00:43:29.860 --> 00:43:31.160
I think it's hugely massive, right?

00:43:31.160 --> 00:43:35.780
I think it's taken this long
for publishers to realize

00:43:35.780 --> 00:43:39.530
that young girls love comics.

00:43:39.530 --> 00:43:42.500
You know? It took-- like
Raina had a really hard time--

00:43:42.500 --> 00:43:43.800
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna: Raina Telgemeier.

00:43:43.800 --> 00:43:45.100
&gt;&gt; Gene Luen Yang: Had a
really hard time selling Smile

00:43:45.100 --> 00:43:47.870
and now everybody-- every publisher
is trying to get their own Smile.

00:43:47.870 --> 00:43:49.170
I think it's-- I think
it's wonderful.

00:43:49.170 --> 00:43:50.470
I think it's amazing.

00:43:50.470 --> 00:43:51.910
I think it's such a hopeful time.

00:43:51.910 --> 00:43:53.210
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna: It really is.

00:43:53.210 --> 00:43:55.230
I mean I've talked with Scott
McCloud this [inaudible],

00:43:55.230 --> 00:44:00.400
he thinks within a decade women
are going to dominate comics.

00:44:00.400 --> 00:44:02.520
He thinks the pendulum
is going to swing.

00:44:02.520 --> 00:44:05.380
All I will know is like the
first time my daughter--

00:44:05.380 --> 00:44:09.650
Raina Telgemeier was unknown
and she walked up to the booth

00:44:09.650 --> 00:44:13.050
and she said I like
this and Raina smiled

00:44:13.050 --> 00:44:15.440
because there was something there.

00:44:15.440 --> 00:44:16.740
And I listened--

00:44:16.740 --> 00:44:18.040
&gt;&gt; Gene Luen Yang:
And then millions of--

00:44:18.040 --> 00:44:19.980
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna: Millions
topping the best seller list.

00:44:19.980 --> 00:44:21.280
Yeah. Absolutely.

00:44:21.280 --> 00:44:22.580
&gt;&gt; Gene Luen Yang: It's an
incredibly hopeful time to be--

00:44:22.580 --> 00:44:23.880
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna: Yeah.

00:44:23.880 --> 00:44:25.180
So, as you travel around,
you're seeing--

00:44:25.180 --> 00:44:26.480
&gt;&gt; Gene Luen Yang:
Oh, we did get the--

00:44:26.480 --> 00:44:27.780
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna: Did we get it?

00:44:27.780 --> 00:44:29.080
&gt;&gt; Gene Luen Yang: Yeah, we did.

00:44:29.080 --> 00:44:30.380
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna: Do we
have time for any questions

00:44:30.380 --> 00:44:32.750
or do we have-- couple questions?

00:44:32.750 --> 00:44:35.120
Anyone? Bueller?

00:44:35.120 --> 00:44:39.170
Bueller? Yes.

00:44:39.170 --> 00:44:46.550
&gt;&gt; Hi. I work for a company that
makes water filters with writing

00:44:46.550 --> 00:44:49.670
on them for water sanitation
education

00:44:49.670 --> 00:44:53.540
and it's always a challenge to
make things culturally appropriate

00:44:53.540 --> 00:44:57.040
and to do your due diligence
and to make things fit.

00:44:57.040 --> 00:45:00.370
How do you go about
researching cultures

00:45:00.370 --> 00:45:04.240
where you can't necessarily
go-- you have to rely on forums

00:45:04.240 --> 00:45:06.830
or other people, do you-- do
you have to immerse yourself?

00:45:06.830 --> 00:45:09.080
What is your practice?

00:45:09.080 --> 00:45:10.380
&gt;&gt; Gene Luen Yang: Yeah.

00:45:10.380 --> 00:45:11.680
It's hard.

00:45:11.680 --> 00:45:12.980
Right now I'm writing
the new Superman book.

00:45:12.980 --> 00:45:14.280
It's set in Shanghai.

00:45:14.280 --> 00:45:16.500
I've never lived in Shanghai
before; I've only visited twice.

00:45:16.500 --> 00:45:18.790
What I've been doing is
I've been reading a lot.

00:45:18.790 --> 00:45:22.280
I read-- I read books about
what modern China is like.

00:45:22.280 --> 00:45:25.060
I read blogs about people--
by people who live there,

00:45:25.060 --> 00:45:27.230
and I've also gotten-- I've also
been lucky enough to get in touch

00:45:27.230 --> 00:45:28.910
with people who actually
live in Shanghai,

00:45:28.910 --> 00:45:30.950
so I can email them
questions and stuff.

00:45:30.950 --> 00:45:33.430
Like what music are you guys
listening to, that sort of thing.

00:45:33.430 --> 00:45:36.270
But it's always that--
I think it's always hard

00:45:36.270 --> 00:45:39.350
to do your due diligence, but I'm
thankful that you're doing it.

00:45:39.350 --> 00:45:40.650
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna: Yeah.

00:45:40.650 --> 00:45:41.950
Absolutely.

00:45:41.950 --> 00:45:43.250
And one thing you said in your talk

00:45:43.250 --> 00:45:47.080
in 2014 was do the
homework, find people, vet it.

00:45:47.080 --> 00:45:50.390
Find people who really
know it and go through it.

00:45:50.390 --> 00:45:52.390
&gt;&gt; Gene Luen Yang: Find
insiders, I think that's--

00:45:52.390 --> 00:45:56.530
you just can't-- you
can't replace that.

00:45:56.530 --> 00:45:57.830
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna: Yeah.

00:45:57.830 --> 00:45:59.130
Absolutely.

00:45:59.130 --> 00:46:00.430
Yes. Right here.

00:46:00.430 --> 00:46:01.730
&gt;&gt; Thank you.

00:46:01.730 --> 00:46:03.030
Really enjoy your talk.

00:46:03.030 --> 00:46:06.260
I'm proud that I share some
part of your Asian parts and,

00:46:06.260 --> 00:46:08.020
as you can tell, I have two boys.

00:46:08.020 --> 00:46:13.600
And so I have a question,
very practical.

00:46:13.600 --> 00:46:20.240
This is a parenting-- you
have-- your parents have this--

00:46:20.240 --> 00:46:24.510
I guess this extremely
successful parenting model for you

00:46:24.510 --> 00:46:27.510
and your brother, so
I want to do both.

00:46:27.510 --> 00:46:29.880
Please come and-- what
your parents--

00:46:29.880 --> 00:46:33.410
the tips, three or
five, and I can emulate.

00:46:33.410 --> 00:46:35.200
&gt;&gt; Gene Luen Yang: My parents?

00:46:35.200 --> 00:46:38.250
My parents-- my parents-- well, OK.

00:46:38.250 --> 00:46:40.920
So, my dad was very much
a typical immigrant dad.

00:46:40.920 --> 00:46:43.920
He gave me three choices in life:
doctor, lawyer, or engineer.

00:46:43.920 --> 00:46:46.050
And I kind of did one, right?

00:46:46.050 --> 00:46:49.120
I majored in computer
science and I kind of did it.

00:46:49.120 --> 00:46:50.520
And when I was a kid especially,

00:46:50.520 --> 00:46:51.980
I just ended up fighting
with him a lot.

00:46:51.980 --> 00:46:53.800
I wanted to do cartoons.

00:46:53.800 --> 00:46:56.070
He wanted me to do
something more practical.

00:46:56.070 --> 00:46:58.560
As an adult, I look
back and I see that--

00:46:58.560 --> 00:47:01.610
I think my parents had a
point, especially my dad.

00:47:01.610 --> 00:47:03.540
Health insurance is
an important thing.

00:47:03.540 --> 00:47:08.090
And now I really believe
that-- I believe in a balance.

00:47:08.090 --> 00:47:11.470 position:56%
I believe in the balance of pursuing
your dreams while respecting the

00:47:11.470 --> 00:47:13.390
wisdom of your parents.

00:47:13.390 --> 00:47:15.920
While getting health insurance.

00:47:15.920 --> 00:47:17.500
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna: So, if
some of your kids only want

00:47:17.500 --> 00:47:19.090 position:56%
to be comics creators and never want

00:47:19.090 --> 00:47:20.860
to do anything else,
you're good with that?

00:47:20.860 --> 00:47:22.160
&gt;&gt; Gene Luen Yang: No.

00:47:22.160 --> 00:47:25.770
Well, what I would tell them-- what
I would tell them is this-- is--

00:47:25.770 --> 00:47:28.340
is in order for-- I--
in order for you--

00:47:28.340 --> 00:47:30.830
so, not every cartoonist agrees
with me and there are plenty

00:47:30.830 --> 00:47:33.430
of successful cartoonists that
use a different model, right?

00:47:33.430 --> 00:47:38.240
But what-- but the model that
I felt like I follow was this.

00:47:38.240 --> 00:47:39.810
In order for you to protect--

00:47:39.810 --> 00:47:41.550
perfect your craft--
not even perfect it.

00:47:41.550 --> 00:47:43.220
In order for you to
work on your craft,

00:47:43.220 --> 00:47:45.470
it's going to take you
10 years of losing money.

00:47:45.470 --> 00:47:48.090
At least 10 years of losing money.

00:47:48.090 --> 00:47:50.420
How are you going to feed
yourself those 10 years?

00:47:50.420 --> 00:47:52.630
If you're planning on
feeding yourself with art,

00:47:52.630 --> 00:47:55.460 position:56%
you're going to end up drawing
things that you do not want to draw.

00:47:55.460 --> 00:47:57.010
That is not going to help
you develop as an artist.

00:47:57.010 --> 00:47:58.750
So, you need to find some other way

00:47:58.750 --> 00:48:00.890
of feeding yourself while
you work on that art.

00:48:00.890 --> 00:48:02.190
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna: Sure.

00:48:02.190 --> 00:48:03.490
And what if your child says
I'm going to feed myself

00:48:03.490 --> 00:48:05.080
on the MacArthur Genius Grant?

00:48:05.080 --> 00:48:07.150
[ Laughter ]

00:48:07.150 --> 00:48:10.280
We have time for one-- one?

00:48:10.280 --> 00:48:11.580
&gt;&gt; So, I originally
had a ton of questions

00:48:11.580 --> 00:48:13.220
about Avatar: The Last Airbender.

00:48:13.220 --> 00:48:14.520
Huge fan.

00:48:14.520 --> 00:48:15.820
&gt;&gt; Gene Luen Yang: Me too.

00:48:15.820 --> 00:48:17.920
&gt;&gt; But, I'm also a
graphic novel artist.

00:48:17.920 --> 00:48:20.990
I actually graduated from
Carnegie Mellon for music major

00:48:20.990 --> 00:48:22.920
and then I got into comics later.

00:48:22.920 --> 00:48:26.960
So, I was wondering, for you, what
was like your step one in terms

00:48:26.960 --> 00:48:28.260
of like getting your work out there

00:48:28.260 --> 00:48:32.050
so people know it exists
and then like--

00:48:32.050 --> 00:48:33.550
&gt;&gt; Gene Luen Yang: My step
one was printing it out.

00:48:33.550 --> 00:48:35.420
Was taking it to Xerox.

00:48:35.420 --> 00:48:37.970
Eventually I moved
to offset printing,

00:48:37.970 --> 00:48:39.550
which was a little
bit more expensive,

00:48:39.550 --> 00:48:41.190
and then just handing out.

00:48:41.190 --> 00:48:43.510
Like selling it by hand at shows.

00:48:43.510 --> 00:48:44.810
That was my step one.

00:48:44.810 --> 00:48:46.780
Nowadays, if I were to do it
over again, I would still do

00:48:46.780 --> 00:48:49.440
that because I love print, I
love holding something physical

00:48:49.440 --> 00:48:53.180
in my hand, but I would
also try to use the web.

00:48:53.180 --> 00:48:57.920
For sure. I think networking
was hugely important to me.

00:48:57.920 --> 00:49:01.390
I met some cartoonists who
were at about the same place

00:49:01.390 --> 00:49:03.540
in their careers, really,
really early on

00:49:03.540 --> 00:49:04.840
and we ended up pushing each other.

00:49:04.840 --> 00:49:07.740
As soon as one of us met an
editor, all of us would meet

00:49:07.740 --> 00:49:09.260
that same editor because
we would get introduced

00:49:09.260 --> 00:49:11.670
and that was incredibly important.

00:49:11.670 --> 00:49:12.970
&gt;&gt; Thanks.

00:49:12.970 --> 00:49:14.270
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna: Well said.

00:49:14.270 --> 00:49:16.350
OK. Well, your wife just texted me.

00:49:16.350 --> 00:49:19.640
She says, OK, you are a genius.

00:49:19.640 --> 00:49:21.030
So, thank you.

00:49:21.030 --> 00:49:22.330
You're there.

00:49:22.330 --> 00:49:23.630
Thank you.

00:49:23.630 --> 00:49:25.460
Please give a big round of
applause to Gene Luen Yang.

00:49:25.460 --> 00:49:26.760
&gt;&gt; Gene Luen Yang: Thank you.

00:49:26.760 --> 00:49:28.090
Thank you all for staying.

00:49:28.090 --> 00:49:29.390
Wonderful to talk to you all.

00:49:29.390 --> 00:49:30.690
Thank you.

00:49:30.690 --> 00:49:32.020
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna: All right.

00:49:32.020 --> 00:49:33.320
&gt;&gt; Gene Luen Yang: Thank you.

